article.description:
Mike Dunleavy scored 17 of his
season-high 24 points in the fourth quarter as the Warriors beat the slumpign Timberwolves 105-97.
article.headline: Dunleavy, Warriors beat slumping T-Wolves
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Six road games, six losses -- and zero hope for a playoff berth, let alone another winning season for the Minnesota Timberwolves. Not even the slumping Golden State Warriors could squander this chance to send the wilting Wolves home from the worst road trip in franchise history with one more defeat. Mike Dunleavy scored 17 of his season-high 24 points in the fourth quarter, and the Warriors mustered just enough late-game poise to hold off the Timberwolves in a 105-97 victory on Thursday night. When Derek Fisher's eighth free throw of the final 2½ minutes settled into the net with 25 seconds left, the Warriors managed to put a good ending on the same day they lost injured guard Baron Davis for at least another week. "Finally the ball went in for once," Dunleavy said after the Warriors returned from a 1-4 road trip for just their third victory in 12 games. "(Shots) going down are the difference in playing well and not playing well, and tonight they went in." Fisher had 16 points and a career-high 13 assists, and rookie Ike Diogu scored 21 points for the Warriors, who blew most of a 16-point lead in the fourth quarter. But Fisher's free throws held off miserable Minnesota, which wrapped up a six-game trip without a victory for the first time in franchise history. "Nobody should be happy with the way we're playing right now, from Mr. Taylor all the way on down to our video guy," said coach Dwane Casey, referring to Timberwolves owner Glen Taylor. Kevin Garnett had 20 points, 17 rebounds and plenty of new reasons to be frustrated with the rest of the Timberwolves, who have lost seven straight overall and a team-record eight straight road games. But the Warriors are too wrapped up in their own problems to regret their extension of the Timberwolves' woes. Before the game, the Warriors decided to rest Davis' sprained right ankle for at least another week. Davis, a two-time All-Star who's second in the NBA in assists, missed seven games and played limited minutes in six more since the injury occurred -- and Golden State went 3-10, falling from contention after a promising start. "I'm definitely going to get back," Davis said. "I don't care if it's three games left, four games left, as long as I get back to my full capacity. I think it's in my best interest and my team's best interest that I get healthy and really let the ankle rest." Ricky Davis scored 29 points for the Wolves, who would have to win 15 of their final 17 games to avoid their first losing season since 1995-96. Garnett snapped at his mates after a loss at Phoenix earlier in the road trip, questioning their attitude and professionalism. "It's not good, but what we're doing now is trying to prepare for next year," Garnett said. "That's the reality. We have 17 games to go. I was just focusing on trying to win at least one of these games on the road." Both teams have endured plenty of drama in the last two months, and both seemed determined to lose this one as well. The Warriors went up 90-74 with 7:01 to play on Dunleavy's 3-pointer, capping 15 points in 5 minutes for the underachieving forward. Minnesota gradually trimmed the lead to 102-97 on Rashad McCants' alley-oop dunk with 32 seconds left before Fisher made a key steal and hit his final free throw. Leading scorer Jason Richardson managed just 15 points on 5-of-16 shooting, but the Warriors persevered. "With Baron out, I had a pretty tough game, so Dunleavy showed up, (Troy) Murphy rebounded the ball well, and Fish had a great game," Richardson said. The Warriors are all but certain to miss the playoffs for the 12th straight season, and team president Robert Rowell acknowledged profound frustration in his underachieving club before the game -- though he stopped short of blaming any specific players or coach Mike Montgomery, who still could be done in Oakland after two losing seasons.

Game notes
C Eddie Griffin played for Minnesota after missing the previous four games with a sprained right wrist. ... With four weeks left in what's likely to be their 12th straight losing season, the Warriors announced plans to increase ticket prices for the second time in three seasons, with this increase even steeper than the previous bump.
